# Conditionals

## What are conditionals?

## Conditionals are keywords that evaluate an expression and decide to run the associated code block, based on the result.

## (Simplified: You use a conditional to only have something happen if a specific condition is met.)

# If/Else, Match

## If Statement

## You use an if statement when you only want something to happen “if” something else is true.

## To utilize an if statement, you must first have something to evaluate for your condition.

Step 1:

| fn main() {     let age \= 16;} |
| :---- |

## Then, you must start your  if-block with the keyword “if”.

Step 2:

| fn main() {     let age \= 16;     if } |
| :---- |

## After that, you must create the condition.

##  Step 3:

| fn main() {	let age \= 16;	if age \< 18} |
| :---- |

## Then, you use curly braces to signify the code you want to run if the condition is true. This is a code-block/scope.

Step 4:

## 

| fn main() {	let age \= 16;	if age \< 18 {			}} |
| :---- |

## Finally, you put what you want to happen if the condition is true inside the curly braces.

Step 5:

| fn main() {	let age \= 16;	if age \< 18 {		println\!("You're not old enough to vote.")	}} |
| :---- |

## Else Statement

## An else statement is special, it can only come after an if statement. They are when you want something else to run instead if the first code block is false.

## To utilize an else statement, you must first have an if statement for it to be a backup for.

Step 1 (let’s reuse the if statement from above):

| fn main() {	let age \= 16;	if age \< 18 {		println\!("You're not old enough to vote\!");      }} |
| :---- |

##  

## Then create an else block directly after the if statement containing the code you want to run.

Step 2:

| fn main() {	let age \= 16;	if age \< 18 {		println\!("You're not old enough to vote\!");      } else {		println\!("Come down to the polls and vote\!");      }} |
| :---- |

## Chaining If/Else Statements

## You can chain if and else statements to have a list of conditions to walk through. However it is not recommended to do so. It is often overshadowed by the versatility of a match statement.

## Match Statement

## Match statements are like superpowered if/else statements. You use them when you want to account for many (more than two) conditions.

# Loops

## Loop Statement

## Loop statements are very simple. Whatever is inside the block, will be done over and over… forever.

Example:  
![][image5]

## But, what if you don’t want it to run… forever?

## Now you’re talking about the “break” keyword.

(Note: break is usable in all loop types, not just a bare loop.)

## “break”, tells a loop to stop immediately. This is regardless of where in the loop it is. If the program reads break, that loop will end.

Ex:

![][image6]

## Labeling Loops

## In case you want to nest some loops, but want to break a loop in an outer scope, you can label the loops, and break a specific loop (either the current or a higher scope).

Example:

![][image7]

## While Statement

## You use a while statement when you want some code to be executed as long as a specific condition is true. Think an if statement but it goes again until it’s false.

Example:  
![][image8]

## For Statement

## You use a for statement whenever you won’t always know the size of a collection but you want to loop for each element of that collection.

Example:  
![][image9]
